  "topic_name": "Endocrine System and Hormones",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The endocrine system consists of ductless glands that secrete hormones directly into the blood. Hormones are chemical messengers that regulate body functions. The hypothalamus links the nervous and endocrine systems. The pituitary gland (master gland) secretes hormones controlling other glands: GH, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, ADH, oxytocin. The thyroid produces thyroxine (metabolism) and calcitonin (reduces blood calcium). Parathyroid produces PTH (increases blood calcium). Adrenal glands produce cortisol, aldosterone (cortex), adrenaline (medulla - fight/flight). Pancreatic islets produce insulin (lowers blood sugar) and glucagon (raises blood sugar). Feedback mechanisms regulate hormone levels - negative feedback maintains homeostasis.",
    "rules": [
      "Endocrine glands: ductless, secrete hormones into blood",
      "Pituitary: master gland; anterior (GH, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH); posterior (ADH, oxytocin)",
      "Thyroid: thyroxine (metabolism), calcitonin (reduces Ca++)",
      "Parathyroid: PTH (increases Ca++)",
      "Adrenal: cortex (cortisol, aldosterone), medulla (adrenaline)",
      "Pancreas: insulin (lowers glucose), glucagon (raises glucose)",
      "Negative feedback: hormone levels regulate their own production"
    ]
  },
